<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHOWS FOR YOUNGSTERS AND THEIR PARENTS TOO; 'ON PROMISED LAND'S' STORY HOPES TO 
BRIDGE A GAP OF FEAR, IGNORANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By N.F. MENDOZA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 On Promised Land explores familiar territory: Civil Rights-era race relations. 
But rather than focus on the better-known and graphic events of the movement, 
the Disney original film concentrates on the inherent drama in personal 
relationships. 
</P>
<P>
 "On Promised Land" concerns two families, one white and one black, and the 
friendship between the oldest of one family and the youngest of the other. 
</P>
<P>
 Set in the rural South of the 1950s, the film stars Joan Plowright, Judith 
Ivey and 9-year-old Norman D. Golden II ("Cop and a Half") as Jim Jam. 
</P>
<P>
 The semiautobiographical story was written by Ken Sagoes, who stars as Jim 
Jam's uncle, Bo Henry. "I wanted to write about a black family that showed 
love," Sagoes says. "My father was not around when I was growing up. My African 
American brothers and sisters need fathers so much. I write stories about how I 
wanted things to be." 
</P>
<P>
 Sagoes hails from Stockbridge, Ga., the home of Martin Luther King Jr.'s 
father. He says that much of "On Promised Land" is based on incidents in his 
childhood that left a profound impression on him. 
</P>
<P>
 "On Promised Land" tackles such issues as familial bonds, loyalties, 
loneliness, friendship, tragedy, pride, pets, promises, oppression and 
repression. 
</P>
<P>
 Actress Ivey says of Sagoes' screenplay: "I love writing where you tell a 
story and in spite of it, you get a lesson, and I think that's what the writer 
did." 
</P>
<P>
 Ivey, who plays the bigoted Olivia, adds: "The film takes an important issue 
-- racism -- and gives it a forum in which to discuss it within families. You 
can discuss it on several levels of sophistication." 
</P>
<P>
 "I find racism very simple," she says. "It's just a fear. There are many 
people living their lives through fear. The story is so much about being 
enlightened and having consciousness raised." 
</P>
<P>
 "On Promised Land" airs Sunday at 7-9 p.m. on the Disney Channel. For ages 8 
and up. Parents should be warned that some children may find a scene with a 
dead dog disturbing. More Family Shows 
</P>
<P>
 Batman and District Attorney Harvey Dent face off when a secret is revealed in 
a two-part special episode of Batman: The Animated Series (Monday and Tuesday 
4:30-5 p.m. Fox). Dent's secret isn't known even by his best friend, Batman's 
alter ego, Bruce Wayne. For ages 4 and up.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 If it's time to put another candle on your child's birthday cake, tune in to 
Home Matters (Monday 1:30-2 p.m. Discovery), which features a segment on 
"Birthdays for Children." Marla Edlestein, associate food editor of Parents 
magazine, offers creative ideas for a child's birthday party at home. For 
parents.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 OK, so he has a few loose screws, but Inspector Gadget (Thursday and Friday 
7-7:30 a.m. Family Channel) is deeply concerned about the environment. With the 
future of Mother Earth at stake, Gadget urges people to plant more trees and to 
conserve water. In Thursday's "Dry Spell," Gadget's nemesis M.A.D. steals all 
of Metro City's water and holds it for ransom. Gadget's discovery of the 
missing water puts a hole in the baddie's plans. In "Tree Guesses," which airs 
on Earth Day on Friday, M.A.D. threatens to destroy America's forests with a 
wood-rotting formula. After Gadget erroneously blames termites and a helpful 
beaver for the disappearing trees, it's not too long before he puts his finger 
on the iron fist of M.A.D. For ages 2 to 12.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Amanda Plummer lends her voice to Madeline in New York (Sunday 6-6:30 p.m. 
Family), where the little French schoolgirl spends spring break in the Big 
Apple. For ages 2 to 10.  
</P>
</TEXT>
