<TEXT>
<P>
 OMEGA AND AFTER: Bloomsbury and the Decorative Arts by Isabelle Anscombe, 
photographs by Howard Grey (Thames & Hudson: $19.95; 176 pp.) . Anscombe traces 
the story of the short-lived (May, 1913 to June, 1919) atelier that involved 
some of the most prominent members of the literary movement. Organized to spur 
interest in the British Post-Impressionist painters and to give jobs to the 
founders' artist-friends, Omega specialized in the decorative arts. The 
ingenuous forms, muted primary colors and faux-naive decorations of their 
ceramics, furniture and fabrics have a surprisingly contemporary look. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
