<HEADLINE>
<P>
ARCHITECTS TO HONOR PARK AT CONVENTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Architect Ki Suh Park has been named recipient of the American Institute of 
Architects' 1994 Whitney M. Young Jr.Citation, which recognizes architects' 
contributions to society. 
</P>
<P>
 The award, named for the late Civil Rights leader who in 1968 challenged 
America's architects to assume professional responsibility toward social 
issues, will be presented May 13 at the AIA's national convention in Los 
Angeles, where Park serves as chairman of the host city's AIA convention 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
 Sponsored by author James Michener and artist Norman Rockwell, Park arrived in 
the U. S. from his native South Korea in 1953. He is now managing partner of 
Gruen Associates, directing the firm's worldwide architectural, planning and 
transportation services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA041794-0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 033019 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
April 17, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Real Estate; Part K; Page 3; Column 1; Real Estate Desk 
