<HEADLINE>
<P>
IDEAS ON BATTLING BIGOTRY, RACISM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Rusty Kennedy asks us to not simply condemn racism and bigotry but to take 
an introspective look at our own roles in either stopping or furthering hatred 
("Is It a Fanatic Few Who Are 'Anti,' or Our Society at Large?" April 10). 
</P>
<P>
 He encourages us to form relationships with others different from ourselves 
and develop respect and appreciation for one another. 
</P>
<P>
 His words and actions will inevitably lead to an increased sense of community 
in Orange County that will benefit all who live here. 
</P>
<P>
 JONATHAN BERNSTEIN 
</P>
<P>
 Orange County Regional Director 
</P>
<P>
 Anti-Defamation League 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Ana 
</P>
<P>
 * I respect what Rusty Kennedy and the Orange County Human Relations 
Commission want to accomplish. I have attended a few of their meetings over the 
years, made a financial donation and have recently started to participate in 
"living room dialogues," where people can discuss issues of race and bigotry in 
an informal setting. 
</P>
<P>
 Over the years, however, I have heard and seen lots of conversation but too 
little action. There are too few ways for Orange County citizens to participate 
in activities to get at this insidious thing called "bigotry." It is too subtle 
and too ingrained to again list the terrible things that have happened and only 
spend one final paragraph on what should be done. 
</P>
<P>
 I challenge Mr. Kennedy to write Chapter 2 of his article and show our 
citizens the kind of things that can be done and ought to be attempted. Despite 
his statistics, my anecdotal experience teaches me this aspect of our world is 
getting worse, not better. Too many see others as biased but not themselves in 
that light. Somehow what they believe is "different" from those other terrible 
people. 
</P>
<P>
 Like that country and Western song says: "A little less talk and a lot more 
action" is what we need. 
</P>
<P>
 CRAIG G. MYERS 
</P>
<P>
 Anaheim 
</P>
