<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIDGE CONSTRUCTION IS ON THE WRONG TRACK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Freeway bridges can be constructed to survive quakes, and we can learn from 
the railroads how to construct them. 
</P>
<P>
 No railroad bridges were damaged in the Jan. 17 earthquake, and passenger 
trains and freight trains hauling tons and tons of freight crossed them without 
interruption.Some railroad bridges are more than 100 years old. 
</P>
<P>
 Railroad bridges are built with wood and some with steel. Some with both. 
These materials are somewhat flexible and after vibration they go back to their 
original position. 
</P>
<P>
 Reinforced concrete used for freeway bridges cracks and crumbles. Just notice 
all the cracks in concrete driveways and sidewalks. 
</P>
<P>
 If they were in a vertical position instead of lying on a surface, they would 
be down like freeway bridges. 
</P>
<P>
 JACK BRONSON 
</P>
<P>
 Woodland Hills 
</P>
</TEXT>
