<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLAYING IT SAFE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Museums around the world employ conservators to care for prized collections, 
and many of their techniques can be adapted for personal home collections. 
Deborah Silguero, an independent conservation technician currently advising the 
Pacific Asia Museum, the Huntington Library and Art Collections and the San 
Diego Museum of Art, shopped stores such as Home Depot and Orchard Supply 
Hardware for the household seismic conservation materials shown here.Most cost 
less than $5. 
</P>
<P>
 For extremely valuable objects, however, Silguero suggests seeking assistance 
from a professional. Conservation departments at museums will often supply the 
names of conservation technicians and installers. Conservation consulting runs 
between $75 and $100 an hour; installation is $35 to $45 per hour. Says 
Silguero: "Even though we don't like to think about earthquakes, a lot of 
people sleep better knowing that their collections are secured. And it's a 
onetime expense." 
</P>
</TEXT>
